        "law_explanation": "UCC § 2-314 implies a warranty of merchantability in contracts for the sale of goods if the seller is a merchant with respect to goods of that kind. Changing the warranty period to 30 days could be seen as an unreasonable limitation on the implied warranty of merchantability, particularly if the 'reasonable shelf life' exceeds that duration. The modified text could be argued as an attempt to disclaim or modify the implied warranty in a way that is not conspicuous or conscionable, depending on the circumstances.",
        "location": "Section 13",
        "desired_official_urls": 1,
        "scraped_snippet_1": "§ 2-314. Implied Warranty: Merchantability; Usage of Trade. | Uniform Commercial Code | US Law | LII / Legal Information Institute Please help us improve our site! × No thank you § 2-314. Implied Warranty: Merchantability; Usage of Trade. (1) Unless excluded or modified (Section 2-316 ), a warranty that the goods shall be merchantable is implied in a contract for their sale if the seller is a merchant with respect to goods of that kind. Under this section the serving for value of food or drink to be consumed either on the premises or elsewhere is a sale. (2) Goods to be merchantable must be at least such as (a) pass without objection in the trade under the contract description; and (b) in the case of fungible goods , are of fair average quality within the description; and (c) are fit for the ordinary purposes for which such goods are used; and (d) run, within the variations permitted by the agreement , of even kind, quality and quantity within each unit and among all units involved; and (e) are adequately contained, packaged, and labeled as the agreement may require; and (f) conform to the promise or affirmations of fact made on the container or label if any. (3) Unless excluded or modified (Section 2-316 ) other implied warranties may arise from course of dealing or usage of trade. Uniform Commercial Code Toolbox About Uniform Laws State Uniform Commercial Codes",
